unittitle.value: Saint Andrew's Society of the State of New York Records

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: The collection contains records (1785-2014) of the Saint Andrew’s Society of the State of New York, a Scottish-American charitable and social organization. The records document the organization’s administrative history, membership, charitable efforts, and cultural events. All material is restricted for 50 years from its creation.

p.value: Open to qualified researchers. Portions of the collection that have been microfilmed will be brought to the researcher in that format and can be made available by Interlibrary loan. Researchers on site may print out unlimited copies from microfilm reader-printer machines at per-exposure rates. See guidelines in Reading Room for details. Photocopying undertaken by staff only. Limited to twenty exposures of stable, unbound material per day. (Researchers may not accrue unused copy amounts from previous days.) Items that include presidential signatures will be presented to researchers in duplicate form.
This collection should be cited as The Saint Andrew's Society of the State of New York Records, MS 2997, The New-York Historical Society.
Gift of Saint Andrew's Society of the State of New York, 2015

The Society’s membership was initially open only to Scottish men and their sons and grandsons. In 1897, membership was opened to men of any Scottish lineal descent. The membership of the society involved many political, commercial, and cultural leaders. During the Civil War, a number of members served in the 79th New York Volunteer Infantry, nicknamed the Highland Guard. Other prominent members include: Philip Livingston, William Livingston, Robert R. Livingston, Alexander Hamilton, John Loudon McAdam, Washington Irving, Andrew Carnegie, James Gordon Bennett, Alexander Graham Bell, John Lindsay, and Thomas J. Watson Jr.
A more detailed description of the contents of each series is included in the container list.

Series I: Administrative Records Scope and Contents Note

This series contains material related to the operations and management of the Society as a whole. It is arranged into subseries that detail the organization's institutional structure, which includes an early treasurer's book, minutes, reports, printed histories, committee records, and office files.

 Subseries I.1: Treasurer's Book 1 Scope and Contents Note

The treasurer's book is a manuscript general ledger documenting the society's income and expenses from 1785 to 1860. Treasurer's records for the period after 1860 exist within the subseries Minutes and Annual Reports.

 Treasurer's Book 1 1785 - 1860 Subseries I.2: Minutes Scope and Contents note

Minutes (1835 - 1989) provide an account of the Society’s activities and include information related to charitable giving, membership, constitutional changes, and other facets of the organization’s operation. Bound minutes are in some cases supplemented, or in later years, replaced by foldered material that includes correspondence, agendas, copies of reports, and the minutes themselves.

General Meeting minutes (1835- 1990) record the larger meetings called by the President to elect officers, receive annual reports, form committees, and otherwise express the intentions of the Society as a whole. These include Annual, Semi-Annual, Preparatory, and various Special Meetings. Bound minutes exist from 1835 to 1960. Foldered material runs from 1950 to 1990.

Minutes of the Board of Managers (1884 - 1989) record monthly meetings that address changes in membership, review monthly financial and charity reports, and attend to other business as needed. Bound volumes cover the period from 1884 to 1966. Foldered material exists from 1953 to 1989.

Some of what is contained in General Meeting minutes in relation to reports and officers can also be found in the subseries Annual Reports. Likewise, information related to the membership of individuals in the Society can also be found in the series Membership.

 Arrangement Note

General Meeting minutes are arranged first, followed by Board of Managers' Meeting minutes. Each set of minutes is ordered chronologically.

Annual reports published by the Saint Andrew’s Society of the State of New York contain summaries of activity which may include: lists of officers and committees; financial statements; reports from Secretaries, Almoners, various committees, and other officers; lists of active members; “in memoriam” notices; and the organization’s constitution.

Annual reports from the years 1873 to 1976 are bound in hardcover volumes. Duplicate paperback volumes are housed separately.

Governance Committee Records primarily document the process of selecting members to lead and administer the work of the organization. The Nominating Committee selected officers, chaplains, physicians, and members of the Banquet Committee. The Standing Committee appointed a Finance Committee and attended to other executive business. The subseries contains correspondence, meeting minutes, lists of candidates, and related material.

 Arrangement Note

Nominating Committee records are arranged first, followed by the records of the Standing Committee. Each set is ordered chronologically.

Charitable records document the Society's mission to provide aid to individuals of Scottish descent. Responsibility for the dispersal of aid originally fell to the Board of Managers, until 1841, when the Society hired an Almoner to investigate cases and provide aid. In addition to the primary fund, special funds were also established for specific charitable purposes, which can be seen in the President's Fund and Scholarship Fund subseries.

 Subseries II.1: Manager's and Almoner's Record Books Scope and Contents Note

The subseries contains ledger volumes that detail individual requests for aid and corresponding disbursements made by the Society. The volumes are in chronological order.

The President’s Fund was established in 1944 in response to the effects of World War II in Scotland. Separate from the Permanent Fund, which could only be spent in New York, it allowed the Society to supply aid to Scottish charities at the discretion of the President. Records in this subseries consist chiefly of correspondence related to individual donors and recipient organizations. There are also administrative reports on the status of the fund.

The Scholarship Fund (1955 – 1992) was established as part of the Society’s Bicentennial celebrations. For the majority of its history, it provided financial aid to Scottish students wishing to study in American universities and vice versa.

 Arrangement Note

Material in this subseries was filed in two categories prior to processing. The first was a general file containing administrative correspondence, fundraising material, program information, and other records. The second contained correspondence and records related to the individual scholarship recipients. This arrangement is preserved under the headings “Committee records”, which is arranged first, and “Student files”, which follows. There is, however, some overlap between the two categories. Each set is ordered chronologically.

Membership records contain information about the individuals who have belonged to the Saint Andrew’s Society of the State of New York.

 Arrangement Note

The series consists of the following subseries: Registers, Member Applications, "Archived" Member Files spanning the period from the 1850s to the 2000s, and "Unarchived" Member Files, spanning the period from the 1850s to the 1980s. The archived and unarchived member files reflect the arrangement of the material at the time of accession. Archived files are foldered, and unarchived files are housed in original envelopes.

 Subseries III.1: Registers Arrangement Note

Bound volumes are arranged first, followed by foldered material. Within the bound volumes, manuscript material is first, followed by typescripts, and then printed matter. Apart from those considerations, items are ordered chronologically according to their date of creation.

 Scope and Contents Note

The subseries contains historical lists of members compiled mostly during the early 20th century.

The Pibroch was the newsletter published by the Saint Andrew's Society of the State of New York from 1944 to 1994. It featured reviews of meetings, member news, reports from officers, pieces of cultural and historical interest, and information related to social events.

The series is divided into two subseries. The first subseries consists of the published issues of the Pibroch. The second subseries, publication records, contains files held by the editor of the Pibroch. The Recording Secretary was typically responsible for editing the newsletter, and the files include mockups, page proofs, clippings, copyright forms, and correspondence. Material is arranged chronologically within each subseries.

Miscellaneous Historical Material contains items of historical value informally collected by the Society. While direct historical documentation such as constitutions or printed histories is contained primarily in the Administrative Records series, this series gathers material such as clippings, reproductions, photographs, and printed matter that complements material found elsewhere in the collection.
